Breast Mass Classification

Jade Oâ€™Brien

Introduction

The goal of this project is to use machine learning techniques to classify whether a breast mass is malignant (cancerous) or benign (harmless).

How do we go about doing this?

When doctors are trying to determine whether a breast mass is malignant or benign, they may perform a biopsy, which is a procedure to obtain a sample of cells or tissue from the mass to be used in further testing. One such biopsy technique is known as fine needle aspiration (FNA) which involves using a thin needle and syringe to collect cells from the breast mass, which are then sent to a lab for imaging and analysis. FNA is the least invasive type of biopsy.

Our dataset (provided by the UCI machine learning repository) includes measurements of the nuclei of the cells obtained through FNA on different breast masses, as well as whether or not the respective mass was benign or malignant. In particular, the sample of cells collected from each mass were imaged, then measurements of the nucleus (such as radius, concavity, symmetry, and texture) were recorded for each cell in the sample. The average, standard error, and worst value of each measurement of the sample were then included in the dataset. We aim to create a model that will use the cell nucleus measurements to predict whether its corresponding mass is malignant or benign.

We see that the dataset contains a lot of predictors: it includes the means, standard deviations, and worst value for each feature. This leaves us with 30 predictors in total, all of which are continuous variables. Please take a look at the attached codebook if you are interested in learning more about the included features.

Diagnosis Distribution

We are interested in seeing how the diagnosis variable is distributed. What is the proportion of malignant to benign entries?

cbPalette <- c("#52E2D5", "#F07979")
bcdata %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=diagnosis, fill=diagnosis)) + 
  geom_bar() +
  geom_text(stat = 'count', aes(label= after_stat(count)), hjust = 1.2, color = 'black') +
  labs(y="Diagnosis", x="Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=cbPalette) +
  theme_clean()

The above bar chart shows us that the diagnosis variable is unbalanced, as there are more benign entries than malignant ones. This is important note as it emphasizes the importance of stratifying on our response variable when we do our training and testing splits. While there is a noticeable disparity, since the ratio of benign to malignant is only about 3:2, this unbalance should not affect us too much, and we wonâ€™t be doing anything in particular to account for it other than stratifying on the diagnosis variable when we create our splits.

This discrepancy is generally even more pronounced, as over 80% of breast masses turn out to be benign.

Variable Correlation

Now letâ€™s see how the predictors are correlated.

bcdata %>% 
  select(is.numeric, -id, -...33) %>% 
  cor() %>%
  corrplot(type = 'lower', diag = F, tl.cex = 0.45)

Unfortunately, since there are so many predictors, and since they arenâ€™t arranged in any particular order, itâ€™s hard to see exactly what is going on in this plot. So we shall use a clustering technique known as k-medoids to rearrange the order of our predictors into highly correlated groups. However, a cursory glance shows us that for any given feature, its measure of mean and worst are nearly perfectly correlated, so in our next plot we shall leave out the worst measures for each feature.

bc_cor <- bcdata %>% 
  select(is.numeric, -id, -...33, -contains("worst")) %>%
  cor()

bc_dist <- as.dist(1- bc_cor)

bc_kmedoids <- pam(bc_dist, 4) # create k-medoids

bc_kclusters <- bc_kmedoids$cluster

bc_kmedoids_cor <- bc_cor[order(bc_kclusters), order(bc_kclusters)]

bc_kmedoids_cor %>% corrplot(type = 'lower', diag = F, tl.cex = 0.55, method = 'circle')

Much better! It is clear to see that the radius, perimeter, and area features are nearly perfectly correlated, which makes sense as they are all measuring the same phenomena, namely the size of the cell nucleus. We also see concave_points_mean has a high correlation with radius_mean, compactness_mean, and concavity_mean.

Next we want to try and figure out what features will be the most useful in predicting whether a mass is malignant or benign.

Here weâ€™ve graphed a scatter plot of Mean Compactness and Mean Radius, as well as a bar graph of Mean Radius. I decided to include both graphs in order to emphasize just how good of a predictor Mean Radius is. In both graphs, we see that a higher value of Mean Radius typically corresponds to a malignant growth, and a smaller Mean Radius corresponds to a benign growth. This correspondence is extremely prevalent, as every single sample that has a Mean Radius above an 18 is from a malignant growth, and the majority of samples with a Mean Radius below an 18 are from benign growths.

Additionally, the scatter plot shows us the correlation between Mean Radius and Mean Compactness that was discussed earlier, with higher values of Mean Radius being correlated with higher values of Mean Compactness.

Modeling

Preparing for Model Building

Finally we will move on to the actual modeling part of the project.

The first step is to create our training and testing splits, as well as our folds for cross-validation. What this does is essentially partition our data into 6 disjoint sets. Namely the testing set, and 5 training sets. We use the training sets to create our models, and the testing set is reserved as a set of data that none of our models have seen before, so that we can use it to get a more accurate prediction of model performance. Weâ€™ve split 80% of our data into the training sets and 20% of our data into the testing set in order to ensure that we have sufficient data both for training and for accurate model assessment.

The process of creating the 5 folds of the training set is known as k-fold cross-validation (in this case k=5). When we are training our models, the first of the five training folds will be left out of the model training, and only the data from the 4 remaining training folds will be used in training the model. The model will then be used to predict the diagnosis of the data from the first fold that was left out, acting as a sort of pseudo testing set. This process is then repeated 4 more times, each time with a different one of the folds being withheld from model training to be used as a mock test set. This serves two main purposes: it allows us to tune the hyperparameters of different models (more on this later) and it gives us an idea of how each model will perform on the testing set.

# seed for reproducibility
set.seed(3435)

bc_split <- initial_split(bcdata, prop = 0.8, strata = diagnosis)

bc_train <- training(bc_split)
bc_test <- testing(bc_split)

# seed for reproducibility
set.seed(3435)

bc_folds <- vfold_cv(bc_train, v=5, strata = diagnosis)

If you look at the above code chunk you will see that we specified strata = diagnosis when creating our training and testing splits, as well as in the creation of our splits for k-fold cross-validation. This is known as stratifying on the response variable and it ensures that equal proportions of malignant and benign entries will be in each split.

Next we will create the recipe for our models. The recipe is basically an instruction manual for the models we are going to train. It tells the models which variables are predictors, which variable is the response, and if anything special needs to be done to the predictors. In our case weâ€™ve specified that our response variable is diagnosis, and Iâ€™ve decided to include all of the other variables as predictors for simplicity and to ensure that no valuable information is lost. Additionally, we will be centering and scaling all of our predictors.

Note that none of the features in the dataset are categorical, so we do not need to dummy code them.

bc_recipe <- recipe(diagnosis ~ ., data = bc_train) %>% 
  step_rm(id) %>% 
  step_rm(...33) %>%
  step_center(all_predictors())%>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors())

Model Creation

Now we will move on to tune and fit our models. We shall be trying out five different models on our dataset, namely KNN, an elastic net, a random forest, gradient boosted trees, and support vector machine. Each of these models has a corresponding set of hyperparameters, or values that need to be specified before training the model, such as the value of k in K-Nearest Neighbors. As was mentioned earlier, k-fold cross-validation gives us a way (called tuning) to test different values of these hyperparameters to determine which one works best.

The process for tuning each of these models is very similar so I will briefly outline what this like below.

  • Specify the models you are going to be using, along with what hyperparameters you will be tuning

    # KNN
knn_mod <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("kknn")

# Elastic Net
enet_mod <- logistic_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("classification") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# Random Forest
rf_mod <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), 
                           trees = tune(), 
                           min_n = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("ranger", num.threads=4) %>% 
  set_mode("classification")


# Gradient Boosted Tree
bt_mod <- boost_tree(mtry = tune(),
                     trees = tune(),
                     learn_rate = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("xgboost") %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

# SVM
svm_rbf_spec <- svm_rbf(cost = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("kernlab")

  • Create a workflow for each model

    # KNN
knn_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(knn_mod) %>%
  add_recipe(bc_recipe)

# Elastic Net
enet_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(enet_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(bc_recipe)

# Random Forest
rf_wf <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(bc_recipe)

# Gradient Boosted Tree
bt_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(bt_mod) %>% 
  add_recipe(bc_recipe)


# SVM
svm_rbf_wkflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(bc_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(svm_rbf_spec)

  • Create a grid for each model that contains the range of values and the number of levels to consider for each hyperparameter

    # KNN
neighbors_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1, 20)), levels = 20)

# Elastic Net
enet_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(0,.5), trans = identity_trans()),
                         mixture(range = c(0,.5)), levels = 10)

# Random Forest
rf_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range = c(1, 20)), 
                        trees(range = c(200, 600)),
                        min_n(range = c(1, 10)),
                        levels = 5)

# Gradient Boosted Tree
bt_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range = c(10, 30)), 
                        trees(range = c(400, 800)),
                        learn_rate(range = c(-1, 0)),
                        levels = 5)

# SVM
svm_rbf_grid <- grid_regular(cost(), levels = 5)

  • Tune each model

    # KNN
knn_tune_res <- tune_grid(
  object = knn_wkflow, 
  resamples = bc_folds, 
  grid = neighbors_grid,
  control = control_grid(verbose=TRUE)
)
save(knn_tune_res, file="knn_tune_res.rda")

# Elastic Net 
enet_tune_res <- tune_grid(
  object = enet_wkflow, 
  resamples = bc_folds, 
  grid = enet_grid,
  control = control_grid(verbose=TRUE)
)
save(enet_tune_res, file="enet_tune_res.rda")

# Random Forest
rf_tune <- tune_grid(
  rf_wf,
  resamples = bc_folds,
  grid = rf_grid,
  control= control_grid(verbose=TRUE)
)
save(rf_tune, file="rf_tune.rda")

# Gradient Boosted Tree
bt_tune <- tune_grid(
  bt_wkflow,
  resamples = bc_folds,
  grid = bt_grid,
  control= control_grid(verbose=TRUE)
)
save(bt_tune, file="bt_tune.rda")

# SVM
svm_rbf_res <- tune_grid(svm_rbf_wkflow, 
                            bc_folds, svm_rbf_grid, control=control_grid(verbose=TRUE))

save(svm_rbf_res, file="svm_rbf_res.rda")

Model Evaluation

load("knn_tune_res.rda")
load("enet_tune_res.rda")
load("rf_tune.rda")
load("bt_tune.rda")
load("svm_rbf_res.rda")

Now we will move on to see how our models performed, and which value of their hyperparameters seemed to work the best. We are going to be using the area under the ROC curve (ROC AUC) as a metric for evaluating the performance of a model. ROC AUC can range from 0.5 to 1, with values closer to one indicating a better model. This metric is generally considered better than using accuracy, as it is able to more easily deal with unbalanced data.

KNN

autoplot(knn_tune_res)

performance_metrics <- tibble(Model = "KNN", AUC = as.double(show_best(knn_tune_res)[1,4]))

KNN is a data-driven model that (in a classification setting) predicts the class of a point by looking at the k closest known data points in feature space, and assigning the mode class of those points. KNN has a hyperparameter known either as k or neighbors, which is the number of closest points that the model will consider when making a prediction. From the graphs above, we can see that a higher value of neighbors performed better in our case. The model with the highest AUC, was the one with neighbors set to 14, which had an AUC of 0.9905 which is really good!

Elastic Net

autoplot(enet_tune_res)

performance_metrics <- bind_rows(performance_metrics,
                                tibble(Model = "Elastic Net", 
                                       AUC= as.double(show_best(enet_tune_res)[1,5])))

An elastic net is essentially a generalized version of logistic regression that has two hyperparameters, mixture and penalty. From the plots above we can see that the model that performed the best actually had both a penalty and a mixture value of 0. Thus this model is equivalent to a standard logistic regression. The ROC AUC for this model is 0.9946 which is even better than the KNN model!

Random Forest

autoplot(rf_tune)

performance_metrics <- bind_rows(performance_metrics,
                                tibble(Model = "Random Forest", 
                                       AUC= as.double(show_best(rf_tune)[1,6])))

The next model we fit is a random forest. Random forests are a collection of decision trees (flow chart-esque models) that output the mode class predicted from each decision tree that it is made of. It has three hyperparameters: m_try (the number of predictors to be considered at each split in a tree), min_n (the number of observations that must be in a node in order for another split to occur), and trees (the number of trees in the ensemble). The autoplots generated from a tuned random forest are generally really hard to read due to the sheer number of plots that they contain. However, a close inspection shows us that with low values of m_try, and min_n performed better with the best model having a min_n of 1, an m_try of 1 and 300 trees. This best model had an AUC of 0.9930 which is slightly worse than the AUC of the best elastic net model.

Gradient Boosted Tree

autoplot(bt_tune)

performance_metrics <- bind_rows(performance_metrics,
                                tibble(Model = "Boosted Tree", 
                                       AUC = as.double(show_best(bt_tune)[1,6])))

Gradient boosted trees are a similar type of model to a random forest as they both are made up of a collection of decision trees. However, where the trees in a random forest are created independently from one another, the trees in a gradient boosted ensemble depend on, and try to fix the mistakes of the previous tree. Gradient boosted trees contain the following hyperparameters: m_try, trees, and learning rate (essentially a value that determines how much each tree should try to correct the mistakes of the previous tree). It is incredibly hard to discern any kind of pattern from the above graphs, but a look at the actual values tells us that the best performing model had a learning rate of 0.56, 400 trees, and an m_try of 10. This model had an AUC of 0.9920 putting ahead of the KNN model.

SVM

autoplot(svm_rbf_res)

performance_metrics <- bind_rows(performance_metrics,
                                tibble(Model = "SVM", 
                                       AUC= as.double(show_best(svm_rbf_res)[2,4])))

The last model we tuned was a support vector machine. These models excel in binary classification problems (like ours) and have one hyperparameter, cost. SVMs work by trying to find the optimal decision boundary (the object used as a decision boundary is typically a hyper plane but it depends on the kernel used) that maximaizes the margin of the decision boundary (or the distance of the decision boundary to the closest points from each class). The cost parameter adds a penalty to term that influences how important the margin is. As seen in the above graph, we typically find that higher values of the cost parameter are better in our case with the best model having a cost value of 1.35 and an AUC of 0.99531. That makes the SVM out best performing model!

Final Comparisons

performance_metrics %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=Model, y=AUC)) +
geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill=Model)) +
scale_fill_manual(values = c("#6CEC96","#55DE6C","#79F8A3", "#6AED80","#4CC360")) +
theme_clean()

Here we have a graph comparing how each model performed, with darker shades of green corresponding to better models. We have the following rankings of performance from best to worst:

  1. SVM

  2. Elastic Net

  3. Random Forest

  4. Boosted Trees

  5. KNN

So the support vector machine with a cost of 1.35 ends up being our best model with an AUC of 0.99531!

Final Fit

Now we will finalize our workflow and fit the SVM with cost 1.35 to the entire training set.

final_svm_wkflow <- finalize_workflow(svm_rbf_wkflow, show_best(svm_rbf_res)[2,c(1,7)])
final_svm_fit <- fit(final_svm_wkflow, data=bc_train)

Finally we can fit our SVM model to the testing set to see how it truly performs.

final_results <- augment(final_svm_fit, bc_test)
final_results %>% mutate(diagnosis = as.factor(diagnosis)) -> final_results
roc_auc(final_results, truth = diagnosis, .pred_B)
## # A tibble: 1 Ã— 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 roc_auc binary         0.995
conf_mat(final_results, truth = diagnosis, 
         .pred_class) %>% 
autoplot(type = "heatmap")

Our final model had an ROC AUC of 0.995 on the testing set which is extremely good! As we can see from the heatmap our model only misclassified a total of three observations. This is about as good as it gets when it comes to modeling!

Conclusion

In total, we have taken a deep dive into our biopsy data and created a model that can accurately predict whether a given breast mass is malignant or benign. In the EDA portion of the project, we found that the mean radius of nuclei in a cell sample is an extremely good predictor of the diagnosis of a given mass, as it nearly perfectly separates the two classes. We then went on to use this information to tune five different types of models. Namely KNN, elastic nets, random forests, gradient boosted trees, and support vector machines. In tuning these models, we found that the hyperparameters associated with each model has a dramatic impact on the strength of the model.

While all of our models performed exceptionally well, the support vector machine with a cost of 1.35 ended up being the clear winner, with a whopping 0.995 testing AUC, making it a near perfect classifier! Due to how well our models performed, it does not really make sense to continue trying to optimize model results on this dataset, as it would not really be of much value since there is only marginal room for improvement. Instead, moving forward it would be more valuable to develop ways to accurately predict the diagnosis of a breast mass without first needing to perform a biopsy. For example, perhaps a neural network could be trained off of imaging of the breast mass itself. While this would be a much more difficult problem, having an accurate way to assess a growth without needing to perform a biopsy would be extremely beneficial for early breast cancer detection.
